- defined as
"
    function automatic int aligner_PARTIAL_LATENCY(
        int START_SYMBOL_LATENCY,
        int EQUAL_LATENCY,
        int PRIORITY_ENCODER_LATENCY,
        int REDUCTION_TREE_LATENCY);

        int latency = 0;
        latency += (START_SYMBOL_LATENCY + EQUAL_LATENCY + max(PRIORITY_ENCODER_LATENCY, REDUCTION_TREE_LATENCY));
        latency += 1;
        return latency;
    endfunction
"
- correct arguments passed in
- PARTIAL_LATENCY refers to the total amount of latency from the input until (inclusive) the registers that feeds into
  the multistage_mux, so this relative to data_g (which could be data_i or the registered data)
    - we start with latency = 0
    - then we add the respective latency since they happen in series
        - START_SYMBOL_LATENCY, latency of symbol fanout
        - EQUAL_LATENCY, latency of equal that function using the symbol fanout and pipelined data
        - max(PRIORITY_ENCODER_LATENCY, REDUCTION_TREE_LATENCY), we take the longest one as both operate on the result from the equal
          instantiations (later we show that the priority encoder and reduction tree latencies are made the same via pipeline on the 
          lower latency module of the two)
        - then +1 for the result to be registered in; overall the aligner needs access to at least 2 words to make rotation possible hence
          the latency cannot be smaller than 1.
